Closures are a fundamental concept in JavaScript. They allow functions to have access to variables that aren't in their own scope. A closure is created whenever a function is defined inside another function, allowing the inner function to access the outer function's variables. Here's an example:

function outerFunction() {
 const outerVariable = "I am outside!";
 function innerFunction() {
 console.log(outerVariable);
 }
 return innerFunction;
}

const myFunction = outerFunction();
myFunction(); // output: "I am outside!"

In this example, the innerFunction has access to the outerVariable even though it is not defined within its own scope. When outerFunction returns innerFunction, it creates a closure that allows innerFunction to access outerVariable.

